==Volapük==

===Etymology===
Compound of {{l|vo|vola||of the world / world's}}, genitive singular of {{l|vo|vol||[[world]] }} + {{l|vo|pük||language}} (morpheme structure: {{l|vo|vol||world}} + ''{{l|vo|-a||genitive morpheme}}'' + {{l|vo|pük||language}} = {{l|vo|volapük||world language}} /  {{l|vo|Volapük||World Language}}, i.e., Johann Martin Schleyer's {{l|de|Weltsprache||World Language / Universal Language}}. [[w:Johann Martin Schleyer|Johann Martin Schleyer]] created the compound noun ''volapük'' (vol + ''-a'' + pük) by both simplifying and deforming the English words: world ('''wo'''r'''l'''d > '''wol''' > '''vol''') and speak / speech (s'''peak''' / s'''pee'''ch > '''pik''' > '''pük'''), which produced {{qualifier|lowercase generic term}} [[volapük]] (any "[[worldspeak]]" or "[[world language]]") versus {{qualifier|uppercase specific term}} '''Volapük''', "the" [[Worldspeak]] / [[World Language]] / Weltsprache.

